* debugger-public-interface-and-on-error — AutoLISP-facing debugger API + --on-error CLI option (+ aldb connection options)

** STATUS (2026-07-23, clautolisp 1.6.3, branch fix-debugger-cli-options)

Part A (clal-* builtins, *CLAL-ON-ERROR*, --on-error) was DONE earlier.
Parts B-D CLI surface is now implemented:

- --on-interrupt debug|ignore|quit (default DEBUG): a process SIGINT
  handler (SBCL; other implementations keep native C-c behaviour)
  applies the policy at the interrupt point — DEBUG breaks into aldo via
  the *debug-break-hook* poll-point entry (continue resumes, abort
  unwinds to the REPL; degrades to quit + exit 130 when no debug session
  is active), IGNORE resumes, QUIT exits 130. A second C-c while one is
  being handled exits immediately (the issue's confirmation prompt was
  simplified to an immediate exit — [pjb] say if the y/n confirmation is
  wanted instead). Variable *CLAL-ON-INTERRUPT* is mirrored to AutoLISP
  and re-read LIVE at each interrupt (variables override the CLI, as
  specified).
- --on-quit debug|quit (default QUIT): (quit)/(exit) consult the LIVE
  *CLAL-ON-QUIT* policy in %TERMINATE-WITH-STATUS; under DEBUG the
  debugger is entered BEFORE unwinding — continue proceeds with the
  quit, abort cancels it. The QUIT event cannot be ignored.
- --on-error: unchanged from Part A; NOTE the implemented default is
  context-dependent (DEBUG at the interactive REPL, QUIT for a batch
  run), deliberately diverging from this issue's flat DEBUG default —
  batch/CI stays deterministic. *CLAL-ON-ERROR* remains a launch-time
  mirror (not live), as before.
- --debugger-ui tui|ncurses|aldb: the per-run override of the persisted
  default-user-interface aldo setting; aldo.conf is now loaded at launch
  to resolve the default (previously hardwired :tui).
- --aldb-listen [HOST:]PORT (HOST defaults to 127.0.0.1; port 0 = pick a
  free port; service names accepted; [::1]:PORT works) and --aldb-stdio
  (mutually exclusive with --interactive and --aldb-listen): parsed,
  validated, stored (cli-options aldb-address/aldb-port/aldb-stdio-p),
  mirrored to *CLAL-ALDB-LISTEN* ("HOST:PORT" string / STDIO / nil), and
  they imply --debugger-ui aldb per C.3.

Naming reconciliation (this issue is authoritative for the OPTION names;
the command reference is authoritative for the VALUE names):

- --debugger-ui replaces the interim --aldo-user-interface; UI values
  stay tui|ncurses|aldb per the command reference §10 ("TUI is the
  user-facing name"), with terminal/dumb accepted for tui and emacs for
  aldb — so this issue's `terminal' value works.
- --aldb-listen [HOST:]PORT + --aldb-stdio replace the interim
  --aldb-listening-address / --aldb-listening-port pair.
- Per the CLI convention (no legacy aliases) the interim spellings are
  GONE, not aliased; the command reference / user manual / man page /
  release notes were updated.
- The default listen address/port stay the persisted
  default-aldb-listening-address/-port settings (127.0.0.1:4301), NOT
  this issue's random-4000-4099 sketch — [pjb] confirm.

Remaining (this issue stays open for):

- The aldb transport itself (deliverable 3): the TCP listener /
  stdio-framed RPC binding the emacs-ui streams, the §10 "waiting for
  aldb to connect" prompt, port-0 free-port printing. Until it lands,
  --debugger-ui aldb (explicit or implied by an aldb channel option)
  fails with a clear "not yet implemented" message (exit 2); a
  persisted default-user-interface=aldb falls back to tui with a
  warning.
- Sharing the options with alfe (the issue's tables say both tools; the
  options currently stay clautolisp-specific like --on-error before
  them) — needs the alfe debugger story (CAD backends have no aldo)
  [pjb decide: promote to *common-option-specs* now, or when alfe can
  debug].
- --aldb-swank (explicitly deferred in C.2).
- --on-interrupt on CCL (the SIGINT handler is SBCL-only; CCL keeps its
  native break-loop behaviour).

See also: ::

- clautolisp/documentation/clautolisp-debugger-spec.org (§10 *error*, §18 dumb UI, §20 emacs UI, §21 start-session)
- clautolisp/documentation/clautolisp-debugger-implementation-plan.org (Phases 3, 5, 7)
- clautolisp/documentation/clautolisp-debugger-design-notes.org (DN-9 abort-from-any-stop, DN-10 aldb RPC)
- issues/open/clautolisp-debugger.issue (parent)
- clautolisp/autolisp-cli/source/spec.lisp (*common-option-specs*; the shared CLI surface)
- clautolisp/autolisp-builtins-core/source/api.lisp (builtin registry; *error*/vl-catch-all live here)

** Context — what exists today

The debugger engine (Phases 0–3), inspector (4), and three UIs (5–7) are
implemented and tested, BUT none of it is reachable yet from:

  (a) an AutoLISP program — there is NO clal-* function that enters the
      debugger. `grep clal-(invoke|debug|break)` finds nothing; the
      `clautolisp.debug` system is not referenced by autolisp-builtins-core
      at all.
  (b) the clautolisp / alfe command line — no --on-error; the only related
      flag is verbosity. NOTE: `--debug` / `-d` ALREADY EXISTS as a
      *verbosity* level (spec.lisp ~line 120, sets verbosity to :DEBUG). It
      must NOT be repurposed for the debugger — see naming below.

So a user who loads a buggy .lsp through clautolisp/alfe currently has no way
to (i) ask for the debugger on error, or (ii) drop into the debugger from
their own code. This issue specifies both, plus the options aldb needs.

This is a SPECIFICATION issue. Implementation lands after, gated on the engine
already merged on the `debugger` branch.

** Architecture

See clautolisp/documentation/design-note-threads-and-terminal-io.org
for threads and *terminal-io* streams considerations.

We'll name aldo the clautolisp debugger.
aldo - AutoLisp Debugging Orchestrator.
aldb is the emacs user interface to this aldo debugger.

The system is based on two threads:
- the main thread, which runs and is being debugged,
- the aldo debugger thread.

They execute alternatively one or the other thru a mutex.
To be able to debug the code that runs in the main thread, it must
have been instrumentalised.

This means it has gone thru LOAD, COMPILE, COMPILE-FILE, or perhaps
just READ/EVAL.  We'll have a global optimization level option to
indicate whether these operation must prepare for debugging the
processed code.
eg. (clal-optimize '(debug)) vs. (clal-optimize '(size))

Some operations (most operations?) are available from both threads.
For example, setting a break-point.

And while all the lisp operators work synchronuously, we'll also allow
invoking the debugger upon interrupt (control-c) of the main thread.
The SIGINT signal will only set a flag to indicate the next poll point
that entry into the debugger is wanted.

If a second SIGINT is received while this flag is set, then the user
wants an immediate non-local exit, forgoing the debugger.  This means
interrupting non-instrumented code.  (we don't want to enter the
Common Lisp debugger). To do it cleanly, we'd have to put "poll
points" at the entry of all autolisp functions (non instrumented ones
too), so a second flag can be set and upon entry of the next autolisp
function, we can perform a non-local exit, or just signal a CL
continuable error, that can be handled by a handler-bind near the
toplevel that will be able to report the backtrace and propose the
user to inspect variables, continue execution, or restart (our
non-local exit) to the toplevel REPL.

See the sequence diagram:
clautolisp/documentation/aldo-debugger-interaction.png
(source clautolisp/documentation/aldo-debugger-interaction.puml)


CONCLUSION: the aldo debugging thread must be started and ready to
work at any time as soon as the autolisp system is booted.


Since we don't have a multi-thread system, we don't need to open
debugging sessions on specific threads. We have just our main thread,
and we will have always an aldo thread available for it.

** Part A — AutoLISP-facing debugger API (new clal-* builtins)
*** Function CLAL-OPTIMIZATION ()

Return: the current list of optimization qualities, which will be used
for the following calls to =LOAD=, =VLISP-COMPILE-FILE=,
=CLAL-COMPILE-FILE=, =CLAL-COMPILE=, and =EVAL=.

Example:
#+begin_src lisp
((DEBUG 3) (SPACE 0) (SPEED 0))
#+end_src

Note: until we have a compiler, SPEED is always at level 0.

The result of optimization level on the two forks of the functions:

| Optimization levels           | non-instrumented fork | instrumented fork |
|-------------------------------+-----------------------+-------------------|
| (DEBUG 3) (SPACE x) (SPEED 0) | pr, int               | pr, int, ins      |
| (DEBUG 3) (SPACE x) (SPEED 3) | pr, com               | pr, com, ins      |
| (DEBUG 0) (SPACE 3) (SPEED 0) | pr, int               | ab                |
| (DEBUG 0) (SPACE 3) (SPEED 3) | pr, com               | ab                |
|                               |                       |                   |

3=2=1
0=0
x = doesn't matter
ab = absent
pr = present
com = compiled (to native or byte code).
int = interpreted
ins = instrumented


(CL parenthesis: in CL we would mention minimal compilation and both
forks would be at least minimal-compiled (ie. macroexpanded).  But
there are no macros in autolisp, only special operators and functions,
so no such expansion/optimization is required or possible).

*** Function CLAL-OPTIMIZE (qualities)

Sets the current list of optimization qualities. This will only
influence the following calls to =LOAD=, =VLISP-COMPILE-FILE=,
=CLAL-COMPILE-FILE=, =CLAL-COMPILE=, and =EVAL=.

Possible qualities:

- =DEBUG= code is not optimized, but instrumented for debugging with aldo.
- =SPACE= code is not instrumented, (thus reducing its size).
- =SPEED= code is compiled to a faster binary.

A quality can also be associated with a quality value, an integer 0, 1, 2 or 3.
The relative quality values stress the priority of qualities when several are given.

Examples:
    #+begin_src lisp
    (CLAL-OPTIMIZE '(DEBUG))
    (CLAL-OPTIMIZE '((DEBUG 3) (SPACE 1) (SPEED 2)))
    #+end_src

*** Function LOAD
**** Loading source files

Loading source files will create functions.  These functions will have
one or two of their code forks filled, depending on the
current CLAL-OPTIMIZATION levels.

Also, a source file contains indiscriminate expressions, not only DEFUN special operator calls.

Theorically, ~load = (loop (eval (read)))~. But we want to be able to
debug the code thus loaded that we're evaluating.

A file containing:

    #+begin_src lisp
    (setq table (big-computation))
    #+end_src

may have a bug in the big-computation that we want to debug. This
means that the expression (big-computation) needs to be instrumented.

We need the compiled-eval model:

#+begin_src common-lisp
(eval expr) == (funcall (compile nil (lambda () expr)))
#+end_src

which means that to evaluate an expression, we wrap it in a lambda,
compile this function (optimization level take effect, generating the
one or two forks of the function), then the function is called, (the
debugging fork is selected given the current optimization levels), and
thus interruptions, errors, and breakpoints may apply.

**** Loading compiled files

A source file such as:

#+begin_src lisp
      (setq total 0)

      (defun foo (x / r)
        (princ 'hi)
        (setq total (+ total x))
        (setq r (list 'foo x))
        (print 'bye)
        r)

      (lambda (method)
         (cond ((eq method 'total) total)
               ((eq method 'incr)  (foo 1))))
#+end_src

would be transformed by compile-file into:

#+begin_src lisp
  (lambda () (setq total 0))

  (lambda ()
    (defun foo (x / r)
      (princ 'hi)
      (setq total (+ total x))
      (setq r (list 'foo x))
      (print 'bye)
      r))

  (lambda ()
     (lambda (method)
         (cond ((eq method 'total) total)
               ((eq method 'incr)  (foo 1)))))
#+end_src

ie. a compiled file is reduced to a sequence of anonymous functions without parameter.
Loading a compiled file consist in reading each compiled function and calling it.
The result of the last function is returned as result of LOAD.

When we have only an interpreter, vlisp-compile-file or
clal-compile-file will produce this explicit transformation.

Note: the code generated by the interpreter compile-file is not
instrumented.  We'll let the loader instrument the interpreted code.

So, when loading compiled files, the wrapping of each form into a
lambda is already done, so LOAD only has to read one lambda, compile
it (this will generate a function with one or two forks depending on
the optimization levels), and call it (selecting the right forks
depending on the optimization levels).

*** Function VLISP-COMPILE-FILE (mode source [object])

Calls:
#+begin_src lisp
(caddr (CLAL-COMPILE-FILE source [object]))
#+end_src

Currently the mode is ignored.

*** Function CLAL-COMPILE-FILE (input-file [output-file [verbose [print [external-format]]]])

=> (output-truename warnings-p failure-p)

A header is written in the fasl file.

#+begin_example
;; INTEPRETER|COMPILER clautolisp 1.1.1
;; OPTIMIZATION (qualities)
;; SOURCE-FILE source
#+end_example

**** Interpreter

The interpreter will perform the source transformation described in
the "Loading compiled files" subsection.

When PRINT is true, each source form is printed.
When VERBOSE is true, a message is printed for each definition (variable assigned, function defined).
These printing are done at compilation time, and have no effect on the generated fasl file.

**** Compiler

The compiler would perform the same transformation, but generate a
serialization of the compiled function with its two forks.

Basically:

#+begin_example
LAMBDA lambda-list speed-fork debug-fork
#+end_example

Each fork being a vector of code (natif or byte-code).
Some green bytes may be added if required.

*** Function CLAL-COMPILED-FILE-OPTIMIZATION (fasl-file-path)

Returns the optimization qualities of the fasl-file-path.
If this is an INTERPRETER fasl-file,
then actually returns (CLAL-OPTIMIZATION).

*** Function CLAL-COMPILE (name-or-nil lambda-expression)

The core.

The function CLAL-COMPILE creates an anonymous function from the given lambda-expression.
Depending on the optimization levels, this anonymous function will have one or two forks.

With the interpreter, the non-instrumented form is basically the
lambda-expression itself (function entry and function exit poll point
are inserted for handling of interrupts), and the instrumented fork is
a transformed lambda-expressions, with poll points inserted.

With the compiler, the same source transformations apply, but then the
lambda expressions are compiled into natif or byte code.

The returned function objects have the following properties:
- name or nil for anonymous functions,
- lambda-list,
- optimization levels (list of qualities),
- docstring,
- non-instrumented fork,
- instrumented fork (or nil).

*** Function CLAL-FUNCTION-OPTIMIZATION (function)

Return the optimiation levels of the given function object (or the
function object bound to the given symbol).

*** Function EVAL (form)

The form passed to EVAL may be created from scratch, or read from some
source file, or some combination.

In any case again, depending on the optimization levels, we may want
to be able to debug this form, and place break points inside it, etc.

#+begin_src lisp
(eval '(progn (f1) (f2) … (f1000)))
#+end_src

To be able to do this, we'll reduce EVAL to the above, with the
following transformation:

#+begin_src common-lisp
(eval expr) == (funcall (compile nil (lambda () expr)))
#+end_src

So basically:
#+begin_src lisp
(defun eval (expr)
  (apply (clal-compile nil (list 'lambda '() expr))  '()))
#+end_src

*** Variable *CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*

A designator for a function of two arguments: a condition (message)
and the value of ~*CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*~ at the time the debugger was
entered, or ~NIL~. (the condition is the error message).

Initial Value: ~NIL~.

Description:

When the value of ~*CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*~ is non-NIL, it is called
prior to normal entry into the debugger, either due to a call to
CLAL-INVOKE-DEBUGGER or due to automatic entry into the debugger from
a call to error with a condition that is not handled. The function may
either handle the condition (transfer control) or return normally
(allowing the standard ~aldo~ debugger to run). To minimize recursive
errors while debugging, ~*CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*~ is bound to ~NIL~ by
~CLAL-INVOKE-DEBUGGER~ prior to calling the function.

Note: the ~*CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*~ function is called in the main
thread. It's up to the user to set a function that invoke aldo (thru
~clal-invoke-debugger~ with a ~NIL~ ~*CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*~), or to
proceed otherwise.

*** Function CLAL-INVOKE-DEBUGGER (condition)

-- the condition is the error message.

Enter the debugger NOW at the current poll point, as if a breakpoint
had fired here (a programmatic break, the analog of CL INVOKE-DEBUGGER /
SLIME's `break`). MESSAGE (optional string) is shown as the stop reason.
  - Requires an active session on this thread (started via the CLI
  --on-error debug, or clal-debug-session below). If none is active,
  behaviour follows *the current --on-error policy* (quit/ignore/print)
  — i.e. it degrades to "signal an error" when there is no debugger to
  enter, so a program shipped with clal-invoke-debugger left in it does
  not hard-fail in production.
- Returns nil on resume (continue), or whatever the resume directive
  yields (e.g. a continue-with-return value).
Implementation: it is a new stop-reason :user-break delivered through the
same *debug-hit-handler* path (poll.lisp). The instrumenter must ensure
the call site is a poll point so current-pp / the snapshot are accurate.


~CLAL-INVOKE-DEBUGGER~ attempts to enter the debugger with condition.

If ~*CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*~ is not nil, it should be a function (or the
name of a function) to be called prior to entry to the standard
debugger. The function is called with ~*CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*~ bound to
nil, and the function must accept two arguments: the condition
and the value of ~*CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*~ prior to binding it to nil. If
the function returns normally, the standard debugger is entered.

The standard debugger never directly returns. Return can occur
only by a non-local transfer of control, such as the use of a
restart function, transfering back to the REPL or quitting.

*** Function CLAL-BREAK ([message])

~CLAL-BREAK~ binds ~*CLAL-DEBUGGER-HOOK*~ to ~NIL~ before calling
~CLAL-INVOKE-DEBUGGER~.  It passes "break" to ~CLAL-INVOKE-DEBUGGER~
if no message is given, and returns NIL if the debugger continues.


*** Function clal-begin-debug-session, Function clal-end-debug-session

Internal function, they're not needed, the main thread is always run
with the debugger ready to jump in.

     Start (resp. end) a debugger session bound to the current thread from
     within AutoLISP, so a script ggercan arm debugging around a region without a
     CLI flag. clal-debug-session starts a dumb-terminal session on the
     controlling tty (the only UI guaranteed available from inside a running
     program); returns T on success, nil if no tty / already in a session.
     clal-end-debug-session tears it down (spec §24). These wrap
     clautolisp.debug.ui:start-session / the session teardown.

*** Function CLAL-TRACE (fn ...) Function CLAL-UNTRACE (fn ...)

     NOTE: TRACE / UNTRACE special operators already exist (api.lisp
     *special-operator-dispatch*) and print enter/exit lines. Decide whether
     to (a) leave those as the lightweight tracer and add clal-trace as the
     debugger-backed trace point (spec §6.4 tagged breakpoint, thno app-side
     printing), or (b) unify. RECOMMEND (a): keep TRACE as-is; add
     `clal-trace-break fn` that installs a debugger trace point on FN's entry
     poll point.

     Indeed. TO_BE_DONE

*** Function CLAL-INSPECT (value [place])

     Open the inspector on VALUE from AutoLISP (clautolisp.inspect:inspect),
     into the dumb-terminal sink by default, or the active session's UI if one
     is attached. Returns VALUE (so it is transparent in expression position).
     PLACE is a form that can be used to get the value.

     #+begin_example
     ((lambda (/ k)
      (setq k (cons 1 (cons 2 3)))
      (clal-inspect k 'k)))
     #+end_example

