  - Should clal-invoke-debugger with no active session START one (dumb, on the
    tty) instead of degrading to the --on-error policy? Proposed: only if a
    tty is present AND --on-error is not `quit`/`ignore`; otherwise degrade.
t
==> There will always be an aldo debugger actif.

For example if we configure aldb, and no process connects to the aldo
sockets, if aldo is invoked, it will print a message:
#+begin_example
Waiting for aldb to connect to host:port.
#+end_example

We could indeed offer the user the alternative to continue (return
from invoke-debugger), return to the REPL toplevel, quit, or enter the
dumb terminal debugger UI.


  - Naming: clal-invoke-debugger vs clal-break vs clal-debugger. Proposed set
    above; confirm.

==> Affirmative. We define an API inspired from Common Lisp debugger API.

** Part B — Options: reacting to some events

We distinguish three events that can be configured to invoke the
debugger, be ignored, or quit the process.

- interrupt (Control-C, ~SIGINT~).

- ~ERROR~ -- an uncaught call to the ~ERROR~ function.  When the
  program catch errors, it can invoke the debugger explicitely if
  wanted.

- ~QUIT~ -- a call to the ~QUIT~ function, or reaching end-of-file on
  stdin when interactive, or the ~--quit~ option.


These events can be configured by ~--on-<event>~ CLI options, or by
setting autolisp variables. Notably, setting the variables overrides
the CLI option which specifies only their initial setting. The
variables may be modified by the program.


| CLI option (both clautolisp & alfe) | variable              | type                       | default |
|-------------------------------------+-----------------------+----------------------------+---------|
| ~--on-interrupt~ debug ignore quit  | ~*CLAL-ON-INTERRUPT*~ | (member DEBUG IGNORE QUIT) | DEBUG   |
| ~--on-error~     debug ignore quit  | ~*CLAL-ON-ERROR*~     | (member DEBUG IGNORE QUIT) | DEBUG   |
| ~--on-quit~      debug              | ~*CLAL-ON-QUIT*~      | (member DEBUG QUIT)        | QUIT    |


The values may be:

- ~DEBUG~ -- invoke the debugger,
- ~IGNORE~ -- the event is ignored,
- ~QUIT~ -- the process quits.

The ~QUIT~ event cannot be ignored, only the debugger can be entered,
or quit is performed.

In all cases, when the debugger is invoked, it's before unwinding the stack.

*** Variable *CLAL-ON-INTERRUPT*

Type: (MEMBER DEBUG IGNORE QUIT)
Default value: DEBUG
CLI Option: --on-interrupt
Description:

Specifies what happens when an interrupt (Control-C, ~SIGINT~) is received.

When DEBUG, the debugger is invoked. The signal(2) haondler sets a flag
that will make the next poll point, either in instrumented code, or in
non-instrumented code at function entry / function exit points to
invoke the debugger.

If a second interrupt is received while this flag is set, meaning the
debugger still hasn't entered, a confirmation is asked to the user,
and if she accepts, the process is terminated (with a call to
exit(3)), otherwise, the new interruption is ignored and the program
continues until a poll point is reached.

*** Variable *CLAL-ON-ERROR*

Type: (MEMBER DEBUG IGNORE QUIT)
Default value: DEBUG
CLI Option: --on-error
Description:

Specifies what happens when a uncaught call to ~ERROR~ is made.

TODO: See the interaction with *ERROR*

If there is not error catcher, then the debugger is invoked. ERROR
becomes essentially a poll point.  The debugger user will be able to
decide how to handle the error (continuing the normal process,
returning to the toplevelREPL, quitting, calling another function,
etc).

*** Variable *CLAL-ON-QUIT*

Type: (MEMBER DEBUG QUIT)
Default value: QUIT
CLI Option: --on-quit
Description:

Specifies what happens when ~QUIT~ is called.

When ~DEBUG~, the debugger is called from ~QUIT~ before calling the
hooks or unwinding the stack.  ~QUIT~ becomes essentially a poll
point.  The debugger user will be able to decide how to handle the
error (continuing the normal process, returning to the toplevelREPL,
continuing quitting, calling another function, etc).

*** ~--on-error~ option TODO

NOTE: This has probably become redundant with the preceding. See if
there's unstated/unmentionned items and merge with the previous
elements.

A new SHARED option (goes in *common-option-specs*, used by both clautolisp
and alfe), controlling what happens when an uncaught AutoLISP error reaches
top level (the §10.1 unhandled-error path).

B.1  Values

     --on-error quit    (DEFAULT)  Run the user's *error* if any, print the
                                   error, and exit non-zero. This is today's
                                   behaviour, made explicit.

     --on-error debug              Invoke the debugger. The debugger
                                   user interface is configured by
                                   other options. This means the main
                                   process is stopped at the error
                                   point, so the user can inspect/step/abort
                                   (spec §10.1, §18).

     --on-error ignore             Continue past the error where the engine
                                   can (continue-with-error: run the user's
                                   *error*, then keep going to the next form /
                                   action). Where continuation is impossible,
                                   degrade to quit.

*** verbosity levels TODO

B.2  Interaction with --silent / --quiet (-q)
     There is no --silent today; --quiet (-q) sets verbosity to :WARN.
     Specify a verbosity gate on the error BANNER (not on the debugger):
       - WITHOUT --quiet:  quit and ignore PRINT the error message (to
                           stderr) before quitting / continuing.
       - WITH --quiet:     quit and ignore print NOTHING (silent); quit still
                           exits non-zero, ignore still continues silently.
       - `debug` ignores the quiet gate for its own prompts (you asked for a
         debugger; you get its I/O) but still suppresses the standalone
         banner under --quiet.
     If a dedicated --silent is wanted as a stronger form of --quiet, specify
     it here too; otherwise reuse --quiet. RECOMMEND reusing --quiet.

*** Naming / collision TODO
B.3  Naming / collision
     Use the long option --on-error with a single string argument
     (:takes-arg-p t), validated at parse time to one of quit|debug|ignore
     (a cli-usage-error on a typo, matching the -e encoding precedent). Do
     NOT overload the existing --debug/-d verbosity flag. Store on a new
     cli-options slot `on-error` (keyword :quit|:debug|:ignore, default :quit)
     and mirror it to an *AUTOLISP-ON-ERROR* transmit variable if useful to
     backends/init files (cf. the *AUTOLISP-* convention).

*** Wiring TODO

B.4  Wiring
     The top-level run loop (run-autolisp-file / run-autolisp-string, and
     alfe's equivalent) consults on-error:
       :quit   → existing call-with-autolisp-error-handler path.
       :debug  → wrap the run in clautolisp.debug.ui:with-session (:ui
                 :terminal :break-on-caught nil), so the §10.1 HANDLER-BIND
                 fires the dumb UI at the error point.
       :ignore → install an *error* path that, after the user *error*,
                 resumes the next action instead of exiting.

** Part C - CLI option: selecting the user interface

| CLI option (both clautolisp & alfe)   | variable           | type                           | default   |
|---------------------------------------+--------------------+--------------------------------+-----------|
| ~--debugger-ui~ terminal¦ncurses¦aldb | *CLAL-DEBUGGER-UI* | (member terminal ncurses aldb) | terminal  |
|                                       |                    |                                |           |
| ~--aldb-listen~ host:port             | *CLAL-ALDB-LISTEN* | (or string (member STDIO))     | see below |
|                                       |                    |                                |           |
| ~--aldb-stdio~                        | *CLAL-ALDB-LISTEN* |                                |           |

*** Variable *CLAL-DEBUGGER-UI*

Type: (MEMBER TERMINAL NCURSES ALDB)
Default value: TERMINAL
CLI Option: --debugger-ui
Description:


*** Variable *CLAL-ALDB-LISTEN*

Type: (OR STRING (MEMBER STDIO))
Default value: see description
CLI Option: --aldb-listen and --aldb-stdio
Description:

Specify the socket or stdio interface used by the ~aldo~ debugger.

- if a string, it contains the host (name or IP adderss), and port
  that aldo must listen to for the UI to connect to.

  By default, the host is localhost and the port is a random number
  between 4000 and 4099 that is not already used.

- if the symbol STDIO, then the connection with the UI process is done
  thru stdin/stdout.

** Part D — aldb (Emacs) connection option

To use the Emacs UI (Phase 7, clautolisp.ui.emacs / aldb.el), the process
must expose the line-oriented S-expr RPC channel (§20.1, DN-10) on something
Emacs can connect to. Specify options (shared, or clautolisp-specific — the
RPC is the same for alfe):

C.1  --on-error debug-emacs   (or: --debugger emacs)
     Like --on-error debug but starts an :emacs session instead of :terminal.
     Requires a channel (C.2). Without a channel configured, error out at
     parse time with a clear message.

C.2  Channel options (pick one transport; the shim is transport-agnostic):
     --aldb-listen [HOST:]PORT
         Open a TCP listener; the debugger's emacs-ui input/output are bound
         to the accepted socket stream. Emacs `M-x aldb-connect` to it. If
         PORT is 0, pick a free port and PRINT the chosen port (so a wrapper
         can read it).
     --aldb-stdio
         Use the process's own stdin/stdout as the RPC channel (for an
         inferior-lisp-style connection where Emacs drives the process). In
         this mode the normal REPL/banner I/O must move off stdio or be
         framed, since stdio becomes the RPC — specify the interaction with
         --interactive (mutually exclusive: error if both).
     --aldb-swank
         (Optional, deferred.) Reuse an existing SLIME swank connection if one
         is present (spec §20.1 allows this). Likely a separate follow-up.

C.3  Defaults / safety
     - aldb options imply --on-error debug-emacs unless --on-error says
       otherwise; a bare --aldb-listen PORT with no error is still useful
       (Emacs can attach and set breakpoints before running). Decide whether
       --aldb-listen alone also starts a session immediately or only arms one.
     - A listener binds to 127.0.0.1 by default (no remote exposure); an
       explicit HOST is required to bind elsewhere, and should warn.
     - Store channel config on cli-options slots; alfe and clautolisp share
       the parsing (the RPC shim is identical).

Open questions (Part C)
  - --debugger emacs|terminal as a UI selector orthogonal to --on-error, vs
    folding emacs into --on-error values? RECOMMEND a separate --debugger
    UI selector (terminal default | ncurses | emacs) + --on-error policy;
    they compose: `--on-error debug --debugger ncurses`. This is cleaner than
    a debug-emacs value and also exposes the ncurses UI from the CLI.
  - Should aldb options live in *common-option-specs* (shared) or be
    clautolisp/alfe tool-specific? The RPC is shared, so shared is fine;
    confirm.

** Deliverables when this is implemented


1. clal-* builtins (Part A) in autolisp-builtins-core, with the engine wired
   in (a new :user-break stop reason in clautolisp.debug). Builtins-core gains
   a dependency on clautolisp.debug + clautolisp.debug.ui (or an injected hook
   to avoid the dependency, mirroring the DN-1/DN-4 inversion — PREFER the
   hook so builtins-core stays UI-free).
2. --on-error (Part B) + --debugger UI selector (Part C) in
   autolisp-cli/source/spec.lisp (*common-option-specs*), new cli-options
   slots, --help text, and parse-time validation; wired into the run loops of
   tools/clautolisp/source/main.lisp and the alfe entry point.
3. aldb channel options (Part C) + the listener/stdio plumbing binding the
   emacs-ui streams.
4. Tests: CLI parse tests for the new options (incl. validation errors and
   the --quiet gate); an end-to-end --on-error debug test driving the dumb UI
   over piped stdin/stdout; a clal-invoke-debugger test through the engine.
5. Docs: clautolisp-user-manual + the debugger spec's §10/§18/§20 cross-refs;
   man pages; a DN entry for the builtins-core/debug dependency-inversion
   decision. Version bump per policy (feature ⇒ ≥ 1.2.0 given the new
   user-facing surface; confirm with the version convention).

** Naming decisions to confirm with the author (summary)


  - clal-invoke-debugger / clal-break / clal-debug-session / clal-inspect set.
  - --on-error quit|debug|ignore (default quit); reuse --quiet for silence.
  - --debugger terminal|ncurses|emacs as an orthogonal UI selector (preferred)
    vs an --on-error debug-emacs value.
  - --aldb-listen / --aldb-stdio transport; 127.0.0.1 default bind.
  - Keep TRACE special operator; add a debugger-backed trace point separately.

  - The debugger itself will be named aldo (Auto Lisp Debugging Orchestrator).

